snippet.textDisplay: Dan is right that the first 45 minutes of this movie was cleaning up the mess left by Episode VIII. That's a good thing. It badly needed cleaning up. Rian Johnson's demolition act was fine in theory but dismal in execution and didn't add a single thing to Star Wars. One of the first rule of story is to give the audience something to say "yes" to, but Johnson was just a big "no" to everything that had been built before him. Why praise a kindergartener for knocking over his older brother's carefully made model?

snippet.textDisplay:
I love how ironically every critic who loved "The Last Jedi" all are saying that they are upset that the film is tonally inconsistent with the previous film, which is what every major fan criticism of "The Last Jedi" was saying about that film. And it's funny, that they are upset that this film does to "The Last Jedi" what it did to "The Force Awakens" but when it was done in that film, it was provocative and brave and bold, but now it's fan service, and retreading. This guy complains of a lack of consistency with this film to it's predecessor, but that was what "The Last Jedi" was to all 7 films before it.

And the guy in this video is literally parroting every fanboy he trashed for bashing The Last Jedi, in trashing The Rise Of Skywalker. It's so funny to hear him say, "I wished they would have continued down the direction of The Last Jedi" which is the only thing any of the other fans of the 7 movies prior to that film was wishing that film would have done.

Look I saw the film. I didn't love it as much as I loved A New Hope, Empire Strikes Back, and The Force Awakens, but I didn't hate anything in the film either. Ultimately I would give the film 7/10. I feel it is the most "Star Wars" Star Wars Film Ever. If you could sum up ALL of the GOOD and ALL of the BAD of the entire 9 episodic saga, you will end up with this movie. If you have never seen any of the Star Wars movies then this film is literally everything about that story in one.
